Now I have a comprehensive picture of TigerBeetle's test naming conventions across many files. Let me compile the full analysis.

---

## TigerBeetle Unit Test Naming Convention

TigerBeetle uses a consistent and recognizable set of patterns for naming `test "..."` blocks across their Zig codebase. Here is a thorough breakdown with concrete examples.

---

### Pattern 1: `"TypeName verb/description"` — Most Common General Form

The predominant pattern is **`TypeName` followed by a short description of what is being exercised**, separated by a space. No colons, no underscores in the label itself.

From [`src/vsr/free_set.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/vsr/free_set.zig):
```zig
test "FreeSet block shard count" { ... }
test "FreeSet highest_address_acquired" { ... }
test "FreeSet acquire/release" { ... }
```

From [`src/lsm/segmented_array.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/lsm/segmented_array.zig):
```zig
test "SortedSegmentedArray duplicate elements" { ... }
```

From [`src/list.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/list.zig):
```zig
test "DoublyLinkedList LIFO" { ... }
test "DoublyLinkedList fuzz" { ... }
```

From [`src/vsr/checksum.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/vsr/checksum.zig):
```zig
test "checksum empty" { ... }
test "checksum test vectors" { ... }
test "checksum simple fuzzing" { ... }
test "checksum stability" { ... }
```

From [`src/vsr/marzullo.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/vsr/marzullo.zig):
```zig
test "marzullo" { ... }
```

---

### Pattern 2: `"TypeName: operation/scenario"` — Colon-Separated Variant

A second variant uses a **colon after the type name** to introduce the specific scenario. This appears in files like [`src/queue.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/queue.zig), [`src/stack.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stack.zig), and [`src/stdx/ring_buffer.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/ring_buffer.zig):

```zig
// src/queue.zig
test "Queue: push/pop/peek/remove/empty" { ... }
test "Queue: fuzz" { ... }

// src/stack.zig
test "Stack: fuzz" { ... }
test "Stack: push/pop/peek/empty" { ... }

// src/stdx/ring_buffer.zig
test "RingBuffer: low level interface" { ... }
test "RingBuffer: push/pop high level interface" { ... }
```

---

### Pattern 3: `"module_name description"` — Snake_case Module Name

When the subject is a module or function rather than a type, the module name is used verbatim (often matching the filename), followed by a plain-English description:

From [`src/ewah.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/ewah.zig):
```zig
test "ewah encode→decode cycle" { ... }
test "ewah Word=u8" { ... }
test "ewah Word=u16" { ... }
```

---

### Pattern 4: `"module_name: scenario"` — Colon After Module Name

The colon variant is also used for module-level tests. From [`src/lsm/binary_search.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/lsm/binary_search.zig):

```zig
test "binary search: exhaustive" { ... }
test "binary search: explicit" { ... }
test "binary search: duplicates" { ... }
test "binary search: random" { ... }
test "binary search: explicit range" { ... }
test "binary search: duplicated range" { ... }
test "binary search: random range" { ... }
```

And from [`src/lsm/k_way_merge.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/lsm/k_way_merge.zig):
```zig
test "k_way_merge: unit" { ... }
test "k_way_merge: exhaustigen" { ... }
```

---

### Summary of the Convention

| Sub-pattern | Format | Example Files |
|---|---|---|
| Type + description | `"TypeName description"` | `free_set.zig`, `list.zig`, `checksum.zig` |
| Type + colon + ops | `"TypeName: op/op/op"` | `queue.zig`, `stack.zig`, `ring_buffer.zig` |
| Module + description | `"module_name description"` | `ewah.zig` |
| Module + colon + scenario | `"module_name: scenario"` | `binary_search.zig`, `k_way_merge.zig` |

**Key observations:**

1. **The subject is always first** — either the type name (PascalCase) or the module name (snake_case), matching what the file implements.
2. **No `test_` prefix** — unlike many languages, tests are never named `test_something`. The label is a natural English description.
3. **The colon `:` is used to separate a subject from a scenario**, functioning like a subheading. It is common but not universal — some files use just a space.
4. **Scenario labels are descriptive and lowercase** — e.g., `"exhaustive"`, `"fuzz"`, `"duplicate elements"`, `"encode→decode cycle"`.
5. **Operation lists** are separated by `/` when multiple operations are being tested together: e.g., `"push/pop/peek/remove/empty"`.
6. **Fuzzing tests** are consistently labeled with `fuzz` as the scenario: e.g., `"DoublyLinkedList fuzz"`, `"Queue: fuzz"`, `"Stack: fuzz"`.
7. **Unicode** is occasionally used in labels for clarity, e.g., `"ewah encode→decode cycle"`.

